Hash functions, public keys, and private keys
> They're basically the "Mejirushi-Seals"(目印留) from Yu Yu Hakusho.

Public Key
> Think of it like a box with an open lid.
  Anyone can toss something inside, but once it snaps shut, only the sender can open it. 

Private Key
> That's literally YOU!
  It’s like being registered for iris or vein scans—if you end up with a glass eye,
  lose the registered body part, or well... die, the auth fails.
  So don't lose it, and for the love of god, don't die!

Hash Function
> The Mejirushi-Seal (sticker) tells you the exact state of the person who slapped it on just by looking at it.
  You could say it’s pretty damn close to compressing a person (and their current state) into data.

Public Key (The Mejirushi-Seal Version)
> In the original manga, everyone writes their name on the Mejirushi-Seal (sticker) before putting it on,
  so you know exactly whose Mejirushi-Seal (sticker) is whose.
  That gives off major public key vibes.

Private Key (The Mejirushi-Seal Version)
> A Mejirushi-Seal (sticker) can only be peeled off by the person who put it there.
  It reacts to their "Kimon" (spiritual fingerprint), which is completely unique to every individual.
  The fact that an active Mejirushi-Seal (sticker) only responds to that specific Kimon is pure private key energy.

(Note: In the manga, the Mejirushi-Seal naturally falls off if the person dies, but I figured that part doesn't really fit the Web3 analogy).*

